&#xa0;
defaultWritten evidence submitted by Amnesty International UKdefault&#xa0;defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;
defaultAmnesty International (AI) welcomes the Commons Liaison Committee’s focus on violence against women and girls for its session with the Prime Minister on Tuesday 14 January 2014. Through our work focusing on improving protection for women’s human rights, our concerns span both foreign and domestic policy.
default&#xa0;
defaultA report by the World Health Organisation in 2013, drawing together data from a range of studies, found that worldwide 35% of women have experienced violence, and that the consequences can be devastating. The statistics for the UK alone
default indicate that violence against women and girls should be a priority for the UK Government.
default&#xa0;
defaultAI welcomed the UK Government’s Call to End Violence Against Women and Girls, yet despite the commitments laid out in this strategy, AI is concerned that approaches across government departments are still ad hoc, and that a consistent understanding and approach to violence against women and girls across all government policy areas is still lacking.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is AI’s view that protection and support for women human rights defenders, support for women’s rights organisations, investment in specialist women’s support services, and a strong programme of work on prevention
default 
defaultare crucial components to any government strategy to address violence against women, whether applied to international or domestic policies. AI is particularly concerned that the UK Government has not taken a consistent approach to ensure that these measures are integral to its work in addressing violence against women and girls across government.
default&#xa0;
defaultDFID’s commitment to VAWGdefault&#xa0;defaultAmnesty International welcomes 
defaultthe 
defaultDepartment for International Development (DFID)
default’s
default widening remit of its Country Programmes to include addressing VAWG in 27 countries, especially the incorporation of VAWG as a strategic priority in Afghanistan, however work on the ground remains thin with only 3 out of 27 country programmes having VAWGs as a strategic priority. 
